	   <a name=102147670015212></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f102147670015212><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=102147670015212>Multiple mobs</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=102147670015212#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=12608><span id=Scholar>XanPrime Defender of Justice</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>19 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, May 15th 11:40 AM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I have a question for the forum that relates to a Mage soloing multiple mobs.<br><br>The problem that I run into no matter what pet I use is when the pet is fighting two or more mobs and one decides to aggro on me.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br><br>I try using the /pet back off command, but by the time the pet decides to listen to me and attack the mob on me, the one that it was fighting hits him and takes his attention.  At this point, his poor master is getting the tar beated out of him as he faithfully solos the other mob.<br><br>I've tried the Run-At-Your-Pet but I've found that to be neigh ineffective.<br><br>So what happens is that my pet ends up soloing one or more mobs as I desperately try to nuke the one on my inbetween its poundings of me.<br><br>Any advice, Magicians?  I enjoy my soloing, but any more than one mob and I'm in serious danger.<br>&nbsp;<br>======================<br>Madrigan 53 Erudite Elementalist<br>Itarax 41 Iksar Shaman<br>Vetachi 25 Iksar Monk<br>Balorinx 25 Halfling Rogue</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>
<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%>
	   <a name=102150412416952></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f102150412416952><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=102150412416952>RE: Multiple mobs</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=102150412416952#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=73372><span id=Sage>Malaclypse</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>142 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, May 15th 7:17 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.90]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>It's a bit of a trick. In order to understand this you need to know a bit about how mobs aggro.<br><br>Ok here we go, aggro 101.<br><br>Now, if you're fighting a mob where they're KoS to you and not your pet, they will keep aggro on you until your pet attacks them and starts doing damage.<br><br>If you're attacking a mob that is kos to you AND your pet, as long as you pulled without doing damage, such as walking up into aggro range and running, they will be aggro on you until they get into aggro range of your pet, then if you're far enough back they *should* switch. That's when running back and forth over your pet works. Also tho, if they start to whomp on ya first, You go up on their hate list so they're likely to ignore your pet and go for you.<br><br>Now, there are basically two types of mob groups. Social and Non-Social. Social means that if you pull one, you're going to get one very interested in you and a bunch that are out to assist it. So if you send your pet into a social group of mobs, all the aggro should be on it until you start nuking. More on that later.<br><br>Non-Social means that while the mob group might be aggro to you and your pet, they won't assist each other. This means that you can nuke and pull freely without having to worry about adds, long as you don't step into aggro range of one. Plaguebone Thieves in DL are an example of these. Fairly certain that your level can effect how social mobs are.<br><br>Now, Your problem is keeping aggro on your pet, so here's what ya need to keep in mind. If you're pulling a group of social mobs, (which I'm assuming you are) You're going to end up with the mob you pulled having you pretty high on its hate list and the others just on there. So if they're KoS to you and your pet, all you need to do is have your pet rush them before they get to you, and they'll go after it rather than you. Otherwise you need to play tag. Here's why the AA Skill /Pet Hold is so coveted. What you need to do is have it tag one of em, then call it off (hotkey /pet back off. Always.) and before the mob it was fighting gets another hit in, make it attack the second one.<br><br>Now, while your pet is KoS to whatever you're fighting (maybe), they're not KoS to your pet, which means that after the first one starts smacking it again, it's gonna switch back to the first one. However, it will have damaged both of them, and you'll probably only have damaged one, which means that they'll both be aggro on it. Even if your pet missed the second one, it still goes up on it's hate list for attempting to thwak it, so yer still good. <br><br>Where /pet hold comes in handy is that it will actually STOP attacking the first one and switch to the second one regardless of it's personal hate list, that means you can easily ensure that aggro stays on your pet at all times.<br><br>Now here's where it gets tricky. You have both of em aggroed on your pet, now ya gotta keep em there while making sure that your pet doesn't die.<br><br>In EQ everything is determined by ticks. A tick in eq is 4 seconds real time. Every tick, your spot on the mobs hatelist drops and your pets goes up, depending on how much damage it does. What you need to do is nuke the one it's attacking and ONLY that one to start with. If ya nuke the second one, that one's gonna make a bee-line for ya which can make life VERY complicated.<br><br>Now, when to nuke that first one is critical, and that you really have to learn from experience. The earring foci can help with this due to their aggro reduction, but basically what you need to do is make sure that your pet has done enough damage so that when you nuke it, you won't end up higher than your pet on the mob's hate list. Not sure on the exact formula for figuring that out, you have to sort of learn to feel it out. Experiment on solo pulls.<br><br>So basically, you nuke down the first one, healing your pet occasionally with your pet damage shielded, then when the first mob drops, do the same to the second one. If you DO get aggro, then you can run back and forth over your pet for a couple ticks till it gets back to the top of the hate list.<br><br>Another thing to keep in mind is HOW you pull stuff. If you're just nuking one and drawing the second in as an add, then this will work fairly easily, otherwise you have work a lot harder to get your pet to the top of the second mob's hatelist, and that's when it can get bloody annoying. Air pets work great for tag because as soon as they stun, you have a small window where the first mob won't attack and you can freely make your pet aggro the second. <br><br>Oh, and don't pull multiple mobs with a point blank area of effect like fireflux, otherwise you're gonna have to make your pet tag that second mob a lot more.<br><br>On single mobs, 3 wave rain AoEs like rain of fire and rain of spikes can do pretty well as a low aggro nuke. A burned out pet can usually outdamage the waves as they occur. Be ready to kite it tho ;)<br><br><br><br>Faelawen Starfyre, The Mad Mage of Povar, 48th season, Leader of Defiant Heroes.<br><br>PS: This is an extrordinarly hard topic to write about, as a lot of this knowledge is subliminal for high level mages. If anyone has anything to correct or add, please feel free.<br><br>PPS: Madrigan your particular problem is that you're probably overnuking the second mob. Just concentrate on bringing whatever your pet is attacking down first, then work on the second mob. <br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
